<p>Good, I hope you will come out against the effort to start the &#8220;No Award&#8221; Voting block.</p>
<p>Frankly, it is the viciousness of the response that has me baffled and it makes those of us who want to be included feel unwelcome.</p>
<p>&#8220;than-ethical means&#8221;</p>
<p>What breach of &#8220;ethics&#8221;? The rules were followed, people paid to be able to vote. The process was followed. So there was a campaign to get certain authors voted for in a popularity contest? So what, we have the same thing every year in November here in the US. There is nothing &#8220;unethical&#8221; about it.</p>
<p>What I can tell you is that looking at the reactions I know which side of the fence is being the most offensive. What it comes down to for me, is either paying members have the right to vote and vote the way they darned well please and if they do then how they vote or why they voted for what is no one else&#8217;s business. Either that or the awards should be shut down.</p>
<p>As far as the obvious personal grudges on both sides I suggest a big ring and those inflatable Sumo costumes and let them get it on.</p>
